caption:
Table 1. From Sparse R-CNN to DDQ: We show the results of adding Duplicate Query 
Removal(DQR), boosting the number of queries to 7000, and replacing the first 4 stages 
of Sparse R-CNN with our RPN, and finally, adding FRF RoI Align and QFocal to get 
DDQ.

Table 2. Comparison with other detectors including end-to-end detectors e.g., Condi-
tional (Cond.) DETR [17], Anchor DETR [24], DAB DETR [15], Deformable (Deform.) 
DETR [27], Efficient DETR[26], Sparse R-CNN [20], SMCA [7] and traditional CNN-
based object detectors e.g., Cascade R-CNN [1], PAA [12], TOOD [6], DyHead [4] on 
different training settings and with different backbones.

Table 7. We regard the 
first 4 stages of Sparse R-CNN as RPN to make a fair comparison with our 
RPN. It can be found that the recall of vanilla RPN and using 300 queries in 
Sparse R-CNN both have significant lower recall than that of our RPN design. 
Although having 7000 query can greatly improve the recall, the inference speed 
becomes extremely slow, which is 6.2 times slower than our method.
